      <div class="about-story-text reveal">
        <span class="section-label">The Beginning</span>
        <h2>It started on a building site</h2>
        <p>Before MUNLER, there was a building site. One of us trained as a civil engineer and spent years in London on large, demanding projects, the kind where materials are chosen for how they perform, not for how little they cost.</p>
        <p>Somewhere along the way, one thing would not let go. Every mirror looked the same. The same safe shapes, the same thin aluminium and pot metal, the same quiet compromise. For an object you stand in front of every single day, it felt like a missed opportunity.</p>
        <p>We became convinced a mirror could be the opposite of forgettable. Sculptural, asymmetrical, made from materials you would trust on site and finished to a standard no one else seemed willing to reach. The asymmetry was deliberate, a quiet refusal of all that sameness.</p>
